Since you are running self-managed Kubernetes on EC2 (1 master + 1 worker) and you want:

✅ Services remain ClusterIP

✅ Expose through ALB

✅ Worker nodes in private subnet

✅ Simple setup

The cleanest method is:

Internet
   │
   ▼
ALB (Public Subnet)
   │
   ▼
NGINX Ingress Controller (NodePort)
   │
   ▼
ClusterIP Services
   │
   ▼
Pods

Only Nginx Ingress uses NodePort, your application services stay ClusterIP.

Below are the simplest step-by-step instructions.

STEP 1 — Install Nginx Ingress Controller

SSH into master node.

Install Helm (if not installed):

curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash

Add repo:

helm repo add ingress-nginx https://kubernetes.github.io/ingress-nginx
helm repo update

Install ingress controller:

helm install ingress-nginx ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx \
--namespace ingress-nginx \
--create-namespace \
--set controller.service.type=NodePort
STEP 2 — Get NodePort of Ingress

Run:

kubectl get svc -n ingress-nginx

Example output:

ingress-nginx-controller   NodePort

Example ports:

80:30080/TCP
443:30443/TCP

Write them down:

HTTP  → 30080
HTTPS → 30443
STEP 3 — Allow Ports in Worker Security Group

Go to AWS Console

EC2 → Security Groups → Worker Node SG

Add inbound rules:

Type	Port	Source
Custom TCP	30080	ALB Security Group
Custom TCP	30443	ALB Security Group
STEP 4 — Create ALB

Go to:

EC2 → Load Balancers → Create Load Balancer

Choose:

Application Load Balancer

Settings:

Name:

k8s-public-alb

Scheme:

Internet-facing

IP type:

IPv4
STEP 5 — Select Public Subnets

Choose public subnets where internet gateway exists.

Example:

10.0.1.0
10.0.2.0
STEP 6 — Attach Security Group

Create or attach SG:

alb-public-sg

Inbound rules:

Type	Port	Source
HTTP	80	0.0.0.0/0
HTTPS	443	0.0.0.0/0
STEP 7 — Create Target Group

Type:

Instance

Protocol:

HTTP

Port:

30080
ingress-nginx   ingress-nginx-controller             NodePort    10.97.2.17       <none>        80:32537/TCP,443:30273/TCP   63m
here we have to register 32537

Health check path:

/healthz

Register target:

Select worker node instance.

STEP 8 — Configure Listener

Listener:

HTTP :80

Forward to:

nginx-nodeport-target-group

Create ALB.

STEP 9 — Verify ALB Health

Go to:

EC2 → Target Groups

Targets should show:

Healthy
STEP 10 — Create Ingress for Your Service

You already have:

gateway-service
ClusterIP
port 30000

Create file:

gateway-ingress.yaml
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: gateway-ingress
spec:
  ingressClassName: nginx
  rules:
  - host: api.yourdomain.com
    http:
      paths:
      - path: /
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: gateway-service
            port:
              number: 30000

Apply:

kubectl apply -f gateway-ingress.yaml
STEP 11 — Test with ALB DNS

Go to:

EC2 → Load Balancers

Copy DNS:

k8s-public-alb-xxxx.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com

Test:

http://k8s-public-alb-xxxx.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com
STEP 12 — Connect Domain

If using Amazon Route 53

Create record:

api.yourdomain.com

Type:

CNAME

Value:

k8s-public-alb-xxxx.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com
